\p One son of Efraim was Shutelah. Shutelah's¦190916 son was Bered. Bered's¦190917 son was Tahat. Tahat's¦190919 son was Eleadah. Eleadah's¦190921 son \add was also named\add* Tahat.
\v 21 \add @Tahat's\add* son was Zavad. Zavad's son was Shutelah¦190928. Efraim's other sons, Ezer¦190930 and Elead¦190931, went¦190939 to Gat¦190935 city to steal some cattle but were killed¦190932 by \add ≈some of the natives of that area\add*.
\v 22 Their father¦190947 Efraim¦190946 mourned¦190945 for \add ≈quite some time\add*, and¦190950 his relatives¦190951 came¦190950 to comfort¦190952 him¦190952.
\v 23 Then¦190954 he \add ≈slept with\add* his wife and she \add ≈got pregnant¦190958\add* and \add ≈gave¦190959 birth¦190959 to\add* a son. \add @Efraim\add* \add ≈named him\add* Beriah¦190965 \add (which sounds like the Hebrew word for ‘trouble’)\add*, because \add ≈of the recent tragedy in their family\add*.
\p
\v 24 Efraim's daughter¦190971 was Sheerah and she founded three towns: Lower Beyt-Horon, Upper Beyt-Horon, and Uzzen¦190984-Sheerah.
\p
\v 25 \add Another son of Efraim\add* was Refah. Refah's son was Reshef. Reshef's¦190989 son was Telah. Telah's¦190990 son was Tahan¦190992.
