\v 35 Mikah's¦191460 sons¦191459 were Pithon¦191461, Melek¦191462, Tarea¦191463, and Ahaz¦191464.
\v 36 Ahaz was the father of Yehoaddah. Yehoaddah was the father of Alemet¦191475, Azmavet¦191478, and Zimri. Zimri was the father of Motsa.
\v 37 Motsa was the father¦191489 of Binea. Rafah was Binea's¦191492 son. Eleasah was Raphah's son. Atsel was Eleasah's¦191495 son.
\p
\v 38 Atsel had \add ≈a total of\add* six sons named Azrikam¦191505, Bokeru, Yishmael¦191508, Shearyah¦191509, Ovadyah, and Hanan¦191511.
\v 39 Atsel had a brother, Eshek. Eshek's¦191519 oldest son was Ulam¦191521. His other sons¦191518 were Yeush¦191523 and¦191525 Elifelet¦191525.
\p
\v 40 Ulam's¦191531 sons were powerful warriors who were also archers. Altogether they had 150 sons and grandsons.
\p All those were Benyamin's¦191548 descendants.
\c 9
\s1 Those who returned from captivity
\rem /s1 The restored community; The People Who Returned from Captivity
\p
\v 1 \add ≈So\add* all Yisrael \add ≈were listed in genealogy\add*, and yes, they're written¦191556 on the scroll¦191559 of Yisrael's kings¦191560.
\rem /s1 The Returning Exiles; The People in Jerusalem
\p Then Yehudah \add (Judah)\add* was taken¦191563 into exile¦191563 to Babylon¦191564 because of their¦191565 unfaithfulness¦191565.
\v 2 The first¦191569 \add ≈to return and resettle their land and\add* their cities were \add some\add* priests¦191574, Levites¦191575, temple¦191576 servants¦191576, and \add other\add* Israelis.\x + \xo 9:2-3: \xt Ezr 2:27; Neh 7:73.\x*
\rem /s1 Inhabitants of Jerusalem after the Exile
\v 3 \add Some from the tribes of\add* Yehudah¦191583, Benyamin¦191587, Efraim¦191591, and Manashsheh¦191592 \add also returned and\add* lived in Yerushalem, \add including the following:\add*
\p
\v 4 Utai son of Ammihud (Ammihud was Omri's¦191600 son, Omri was Imri's¦191603 son, Imri was Bani's son, Bani was a descendant¦191609 of Perets, Perets was Yehudah's¦191614 son),
\v 5 Asayah and¦191621 his sons¦191621 (descendants of Shilon—Asayah was the oldest),
\v 6 Yeuel¦191628 and other relatives¦191629 from Zerah's¦191627 clan (which included 690 people).
\p
\v 7 From Benyamin' descendants¦191637, Sallu¦191639 (Meshullam's¦191642 son, Meshullam was Hodavyah's¦191645 son, Hodavyah was Hassenuah's¦191648 son),
\v 8 Ibneyah (Yeroham's¦191653 son), Elah¦191654 (Uzzi's¦191657 son, Uzzi was Mikri's¦191660 son), and Meshullam¦191661 (Shefatyah's son, Shefatyah was Reuel's¦191667 son, Reuel was Yivniyah's son).
\p
\v 9 In all, there were 956 of Benyamin's descendants living in Yerushalem. All those \add above\add* were leaders of their clans.
\rem /s1 The Returning Priests; Priestly Families; The Priests Who Lived in Jerusalem
\p
\v 10 Some of the priests¦191690 \add who returned to Yehudah\add* were: Yedayah¦191691, Yehoyariv, Yakin,
\v 11 Azaryah, the leading official at the temple (Azaryah was Hilkiyah's son, Hilkiyah was Meshullam's¦191701 son, Meshullam was Tsadok's¦191704 son, Tsadok was Merayot's son, Merayot was Ahituv's son),
\v 12 Adayah¦191716 (Yeroham's¦191719 son, Yeroham was Pashhur's¦191722 son, Pashhur was Malkiyah's¦191725 son), and Maasai¦191726 (Adiel's¦191729 son, Adiel was Yahzerah's¦191732 son, Yahzerah was Meshullam's¦191735 son, Meshullam was Meshillemit's¦191738 son, Meshillemit was Immer's¦191741 son).
\p
\v 13 Altogether there were 1,760 \add priests who returned to Yehudah\add*. \add ≈They were leaders of their clans, and they all were capable and responsible\add* to work¦191754 in God's residence.
